File: economy. JOHANNESBURG - South Africa has reached the fiscal cliff economists have been warning about for the past six years.That point is reached when civil servants' salaries, social grant payments, and debt-service costs soak up all government revenue. READ: Infrastructure investment could revive SA economy: Ramaphosa "Your security services, your policing, education, and hospitals, those expenditure items are being crowded out by things like debt servicing costs and that is on top of this concept that we need to get our debt levels under control," said Fanie Joubert from the Fiscal Cliff study group. "So here we are talking about only servicing the debt levels and we are not actually talking about lowering the debt so again, that is the problem." The tax revenue shortfall has been increasing over the past few years.